\pard\f0\fs28  {\b 9. A.} × {\b versicolor} Willd., op. cit. 2045 (1803) (A. laevis × novibelgii; ? an A. novi-belgii subsp. laevigatus (Lam.) Thell. pro parte). Stem 100-200 cm. Leaves subglaucous beneath, the middle mostly ovate, 2 1/2-5 times as long as wide, the lowest more or less petiolate, with auriculate base. Capitula on more or less elongated peduncles with numerous uniform bracts. Involucral bracts sometimes more unequal than in 7 and with more sharply defined green apex and scarious base. Ligules violet-blue. Locally naturalized. [Au Br Cz Ga Ge He Ho Hu It Po Rm.] (Garden origin.)
\par 
\par    {\b 10. A. lanceolatus} Willd., {\i op. cit.} 2050 (1803) (incl. {\i A. tradescantii} auct. eur., non L.). Perennial 50-130 cm. Stem green, sometimes tinged with purple. Leaves lanceolate to linear-lanceolate, glabrous, not auriculate at base, entire or obscurely toothed. Capitula in a rather narrow panicle, often arranged unilaterally on the branches. Involucral bracts in several rows, the longest 4-5·5 mm, the outer shorter than the inner, not mostly herbaceous, appressed. Ligules white or sometimes violet-blue, not more than 1 mm wide.{\i  River-banks and waste ground. Naturalized in C. & W. Europe.} [Au Be Br Cz Ga Ge He Ho Hs Hu It Ju Lu No Po Rm.] ({\i North America}.)
\par 
\par 
\pard\f0\fs28  Very variable in habit; variants with numerous small leaves in the inflorescence and small capitula have often been incorrectly assigned to {\i A. tradescantii }L.
\par 
\par 
\pard\f0\fs28  The following two species from North America, closely related to {\b 10}, have been reported to occur in France but are perhaps not established: {\b A. lateriflorus} (L.) Britton, {\i Trans. New York Acad. Sci.}{\b  9}; 11 (1889), with patent or recurved inflorescence-branches and very unequal involucral bracts; and{\b  A. dumosus} L.,{\i  Sp. Pl.} 873 (1753), with a much-branched inflorescence and the longest involucral bracts 3·5-5 mm.
\par 
\par 
\pard\f0\fs28  {\b A. patulus} Lam.,{\i  Encycl. Méth. Bot.}{\b  1}: 308 (1783), said to be like {\b 7} but with the leaves entire, not amplexicaul, and the involucral bracts as in {\b 10}, is also reported as doubtfully established in France. It is presumably derived from species from North America.
\par 
